<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-162-708  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 162 708.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DG Review  March 1989 v9 n9 p18(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Truth in databases.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Walsall, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users deciding on a data base system should consider the type ofdata the organization has, how it is logically organized and theform of retrieval needed.andP;  Many organizations will discover ahierarchical data base suits their needs and they do not need arelational data base system (RDBM).andP;  A hierarchical data baseorganizes data in the form of records, where each record has oneor more data items, called fields, concatenated together.andP;  Therecords are ordered by one or more of the data fields, calledkeys, which are made unique by the addition of some type of secondidentifier.andP;  The key uniquely identifies a record and using thatkey always returns the same record.andP;  An RDBM deals with individualfields.andP;  Some unique value is associated with each field to linkthe parts together.andP;  Data is retrieved by defining criteria andobtaining all entries meeting that criteria.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data BasesTutorialInformation Storage and RetrievalRelational DBMSHierarchical DBMS.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Database structure. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>